nodes.statement_tex:
\label{prop:totally-bounded-Cauchy}
If $A \subseteq X$ is totally bounded, then every sequence in $A$ has
a Cauchy subsequence.

nodes.statement_display:
$\sin x = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n x^{2n+1}/(2n+1)!$, \;
$\cos x = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n x^{2n}/(2n)!$.
Both converge absolutely for all $x \in \mathbb{R}$.

